==English==
===Etymology===
'''Charva''' has been in common usage in the North East of England since the early 1990's. It is the predecessor of the more recent and more common ''[[Chav]]''. It is believed that [[charva]] comes from nineteenth-century [[Romany]] language, from [[charver]], the Romany word for "[[prostitute]]" Charver was latin for naughty child.

===Noun===
[[Category:English nouns]]
'''charva''' (''plural'' [[charvas]])

#(''British English, derogatory'') unruly youth; disobedient child or teenager
#(''British English, derogatory'') unemployed youth with poor taste and dress sense

